-- 
Dexia, Fimalac, Deutsche Bank: European Equity Preview

-- B y   V i c t o r i a   T a y l o r
-- 
2011-07-24T23:52:29Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-24/dexia-fimalac-deutsche-bank-european-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index rose 0.6 percent to 272.02. The
Stoxx 50 Index gained 0.4 percent to 2,562.80. The Euro Stoxx 50
Index, a benchmark measure for nations using the euro, increased
0.3 percent to 2,772.60.  Caja de Ahorros del Mediterraneo (CAM)  : The Bank of
 Spain  plans to take over the savings bank, replace its
management and prepare to sell the bank in the latest stage of
its drive to bolster confidence in the financial system by
tackling struggling lenders. The shares fell 5.4 percent to 4.56
euros.  Deutsche Bank AG (DBK)    Germany ’s biggest lender would
have accepted a 50 percent writedown on Greek bond holdings in a
rescue package for the country, Die Welt reported, citing
unidentified people in the financial industry. The planned 21
percent voluntary writedown may result in a “small” profit for
the bank, the newspaper reported. The stock slipped 0.4 percent
to 38.695 euros.  Deutsche Telekom AG (DTE)   Europe’s biggest phone company
rejected accusations reported by Spiegel that it double-charged
clients for database costs. The company is accused of double-
charging over several years and the behavior alleged could have
amounted to proceeds in the “three-digit millions of euros,”
the German magazine said, citing a complaint filed to the
prosecutor’s office in Bonn. The shares gained 1.3 percent to
10.71 euros.  Dexia SA (DEXB)  : The bank that took the most Federal
Reserve discount-window help in October 2008 may face losses of
as much as 461 million euros on its holdings of Greek bonds if
it joins a euro-area bailout plan,  Les Echos  reported on July
23, citing its own calculations. Dexia shares climbed 3.2
percent to 2.13 euros.  Fimalac (FIM)  : The owner of  Fitch Ratings  lifted revenue
in the nine months ended June by 16 percent to 515.8 million
euros from 443.2 million euros in the year-earlier period. The
shares rose 0.5 percent to 27.82 euros.  Lloyds Banking Group Plc (LLOY)  : The lender received “a
number of credible bids” for the branches it is selling, said a
spokeswoman who declined to be identified because of company
policy.  Separately, Lloyds is considering an initial public
offering for the 632 bank branches it is trying to sell after
receiving only two formal bids, the Sunday Telegraph reported,
without saying where it got the information. The shares fell 0.9
percent to 47.125 pence.  London Stock Exchange Group Plc (LSE)  : Nasdaq OMX Group
Inc. denied a report that Chief Executive Officer  Robert
Greifeld  is flying to the U.K. this week for takeover talks with
London Stock Exchange Group Plc. The shares rose 3.2 percent to
1,057 pence.  Siemens AG (SIE)   Europe’s largest engineer’s supervisory
board plans to extend Chief Executive Officer  Peter Loescher ’s
contract by five years to 2017 this week, Handelsblatt reported,
citing unidentified people close to the company. The shares fell
0.2 percent to 93.20 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Victoria Taylor in New York at 
